{{Infobox musical artist | name = Kathie Kay | image = | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Kathleen Thornhill | birth_date = {{birth date|1918|11|20|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]], UK | death_date = {{death date and age|2005|03|09|1918|11|18|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Largs]], [[Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]], UK | death_cause = Alzheimer's disease | resting_place = | residence = | nationality = British | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = [[Singer]] | religion = | spouse = [[Archie McCulloch]] | children = Stewart McCulloch,OBE, Donald McCulloch and hotelier Ken McCulloch }} '''Kathie Kay''' (20 November 1918 – 9 March 2005)<ref name="Dead"/> was a singer from [[Lincolnshire]], known for her radio and television appearances in the ''[[Billy Cotton Band Show]]'' during the 1950s and 1960s.<ref name="Obit"/> Her best known [[sound recording and reproduction|recordings]] are "We Will Make Love" and "A House With Love In It".<ref name="Dead"/>
==Biography== Kathie Kay was born '''Kathleen Thornhill''' in [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]], Lincolnshire.<ref name="Obit"/> She began her career as a tot with the famous Corona Babes Stage School as '''Connie Wood''', then moved on to appear with [[Hughie Green]] as head girl in his gang show; he was later best man at her wedding. She was spotted by [[Billy Cotton]], and first performed with him on radio in 1949, making the move to television and remaining until the show ended in 1968.<ref name="Obit">{{cite news |title= Kathie Kay: Ebullient Scottish singer and television star|author= |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article425460.ece |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=12 March 2005 |accessdate=7 February 2011}}</ref> She also worked with [[Harry Lauder]] and [[George Formby]].<ref name="Dead">[http://thedeadrockstarsclub.com/2005.html Thedeadrockstarsclub.com] - accessed February 2011</ref> For many years she presented her own programme on [[Scottish Television]], where she was dubbed 'the Fireside Girl'.<ref name="Obit"/>
She was married to the [[Scotland|Scottish]] impresario Archie McCulloch, who died in 1994.<ref name="Obit"/>
She died from [[Alzheimer's disease]], in [[Largs]], Scotland, at the age of 86.<ref name="Dead"/>
